title: Politics of West Virginia
added: Starting in [[2000 United States presidential election in West Virginia|2000]], West Virginia began its sharpward realignment from mostly supporting Democrats to mostly supporting Republicans. In [[2016 West Virginia gubernatorial election|2016]], Democratic candidate [[Jim Justice]] was elected Governor of West Virginia. Seven months into his term, he switched affiliation to the Republican Party, making [[Joe Manchin]] the last prominent Democratic officeholder in the state. Manchin narrowly won his U.S. Senate seat by 3% in [[2018 United States Senate election in West Virginia|2018]], a sharp decline from his 24% margin of victory in [[2012 United States Senate election in West Virginia|2012]].

title: Politics of West Virginia
added: Starting in [[2000 United States presidential election in West Virginia|2000]], West Virginia began its sharpward realignment from mostly supporting Democrats to mostly supporting Republicans. In [[2016 West Virginia gubernatorial election|2016]], Democratic candidate [[Jim Justice]] was elected Governor of West Virginia. Seven months into his term, he switched affiliation to the Republican Party, making [[Joe Manchin]] the last prominent Democratic officeholder in the state. Manchin narrowly won his U.S. Senate seat by 3% in [[2018 United States Senate election in West Virginia|2018]], a sharp decline from his 24% margin of victory in [[2012 United States Senate election in West Virginia|2012]]. Before [[2000 United States presidential election in West Virginia|2000]], West Virginia had a Democratic voting streak from [[1932 United States presidential election in West Virginia|1932]], only voting Republican in Eisenhower, Nixon, and Reagan’s national landslide victories. Republican presidential candidate [[Donald Trump]] won 68.5% of the vote in [[2016 United States presidential election in West Virginia|2016]] and 68.6% in [[2020 United States presidential election in West Virginia|2020]].
